PHYTOPLASMAS, STONE FRUIT - USA
*******************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 15 Feb 2019
Source: GoodFruit [edited]
https://www.goodfruit.com/phytoplasmas-in-stone-fruit/


Pathogens similar to little cherry disease are found in peaches and nectarines. Premature yellowing, reddening and curling of leaves, and dieback could indicate Western X or pear decline phytoplasma.

"We looked at some very unhappy-looking peaches and nectarines and found a couple of phytoplasmas [in Washington state]," said Scott Harper, Clean Plant Center Northwest. He identified 2 phytoplasmas, Western X and peach yellow leaf roll phytoplasma, also known as pear decline. Western X is one of the pathogens linked to cherry disease across the Pacific Northwest [ProMED-mail post 20181108.6132710].

Western X, Harper said, might be the cause of peach rosette and peach yellows -- which lead to problems with leaves and fruit size and distorted or misshapen fruit -- noted in the Carolinas and Georgia. Generally, it will kill a tree gradually over the course of 5 to 10 years. Pear decline kills a tree faster, usually within 3 to 5 years. Leaves twist and curl downward, then they turn yellow and drop, affecting fruit quality and size. The problem is common in California, and it's possibly moving north. Plant pathologists know of a 3rd phytoplasma in Washington -- asteris -- but don't know whether it's causing any damage. It begets small leaves, affects tree vigor and fruit size and causes a condition named peach little leaf.

Harper said: "We know material is moving around, and it's very hard to track." The phytoplasmas do not distinguish between cherries, peaches and nectarines and may affect other forms of stone fruit, too. The diseases have no cure. By the time symptoms appear, growers usually must cut down the entire tree.

Growers hope the research leads to some solid practical information about how to recognize the problems in the field, similar to the way cherry growers are learning to spot little cherry disease [ProMED-mail posts 20180108.5545889, 20140127.2233739]. Most stone fruit growers also have cherries.

[Byline: Ross Courtney]

