ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Phytoplasmas of the 16SrIII taxonomic group cause X diseases (such as Western-X, Canada-X; _Candidatus_ Phytoplasma pruni) of stone fruit (_Prunus_ spp). Symptoms and host specificity differ for members of the group. X-disease symptoms in cherry (also called cherry buckskin) vary with the cultivar and rootstock combinations but are often similar to the viral little cherry disease (LCD; caused by 2 closteroviruses in single or mixed infections).

Pear decline phytoplasma (_Ca._ P. pyri) belongs to the 16SrX taxonomic group, which also includes apple proliferation phytoplasma (_Ca._ P. mali) and apricot chlorotic leaf roll phytoplasma (_Ca._ P. prunorum; also called European stone fruit yellows phytoplasma). It appears likely that the report above actually refers to the latter, rather than the pear pathogen. Phytoplasmas of this group are considered the most serious pathogens of stone and pome fruits in Europe.

The aster yellows phytoplasma group (_Ca._ P. asteris], 16SrI taxonomic group) is one of the most diverse phytoplasma groups known. Members cause or are involved in a large number of serious crop diseases and can infect over 300 host species.

Phytoplasmas can be spread by sap sucking insects (mostly leaf hoppers), grafting, with contaminated tools (such as during pruning of trees) and with tissue cultures. They survive in asymptomatic crop hosts or non-crop reservoir species. Disease management of phytoplasmas is difficult and generally includes vector control, removal of infected plants and other sources of inoculum, as well as the use of certified clean planting and propagating material. Such measures require reliable molecular diagnostic methods and coordinated efforts on a regional scale, especially when dealing with long-lived tree crops.

